<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-109-121 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 966 442</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 8 1991 v8 n27 p11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>ATandamp;T plans to start PCN service trials in 3 cities: asks FCC forpermission to test technology. (personal communications networks,U.S. Federal Communications Commission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T has asked the Federal Communications Commission to approveits plan to start experimental personal communications network(PCN) services in three cities.andP;  The company is the firstlong-distance carrier to consider entering the PCN market, joiningcable television operators, specialty firms and several regionalBell holding companies.andP;  ATandamp;T wants to conduct a three-year trialin Atlanta, Boston and Los Angeles, testing technical performanceand determining the types of services users want.andP;  The plan willproceed in three phases: Phase 1, lasting 10 months, will coverdevelopment and testing of software and hardware and of techniquesfor sharing the 6-GHz frequency without interference; Phase 2,lasting 14 months, will be a small-scale field trial in one city;and Phase 3 will be a full technical trial involving a total of1,000 users.andP;  The three test cities will be linked via ATandamp;T'slong-distance network.andP;  PCN features to be tested include callscreening, schedule-driven delivery, call waiting and callredirect.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (Services).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     Personal Communications NetworksPilot ProjectsTesting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>